          "text": "Now I have a clear picture. Here's my analysis:\n\n## Investigation Results\n\n### Scenario 1: Retry with no holding queue\n\n**RabbitMQ** (`router.rs:52-54`): Falls back to `nack_requeue()` — broker-level redelivery with **zero delay**. The message immediately re-enters the main queue and gets reprocessed in a tight loop until `max_retries` is exhausted, then gets rejected to DLQ.\n\n**SNS/SQS** (`sns/router.rs:28-29`): Sets `Duration::ZERO` as the visibility timeout, so SQS makes the message visible again immediately — same tight-loop behavior.\n\n**Impact**: No backoff at all. Messages spin through retries as fast as the consumer can process them. This is a potential hot loop that wastes compute and could amplify transient failures.\n\n### Scenario 2: Reject with no DLQ\n\n**RabbitMQ** (`router.rs:95-105`): Calls `delivery.nack(requeue: false)`. If the queue has no `x-dead-letter-exchange` argument (which it won't, since no DLQ was configured in topology), **RabbitMQ silently discards the message**. No warning is logged despite the doc comment on `Outcome::Reject` (`outcome.rs:25-26`) claiming one would be.\n\n**SNS/SQS** (`sns/router.rs:57-68`): Sets visibility timeout to 0, causing SQS to keep redelivering the message. Without a RedrivePolicy (no DLQ configured), **the message is never removed** — it gets redelivered indefinitely until it hits SQS's retention limit (default 4 days).\n\n**Impact on RabbitMQ**: Silent data loss. The doc says a warning is logged but the code doesn't actually log one.\n\n**Impact on SQS**: The opposite problem — the message is never removed and keeps cycling.\n\n### Build-time guards\n\nThe `TopologyBuilder::build()` (`topology.rs:264-278`) only panics on missing DLQ/hold queues for **sequenced** topics (and only when `allow_message_loss` is not set). **Non-sequenced topics have zero guards** — you can configure `max_retries: 5` with no hold queues and no DLQ, and nothing warns you.\n\n### Summary of gaps\n\n| Sc