            "content": "# Missing Queue Safety Implementation Plan\n\n> **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.\n\n**Goal:** Prevent silent message loss when DLQ is missing and prevent tight retry loops when hold queues are missing — for both RabbitMQ and SNS/SQS backends.\n\n**Architecture:** Three layers of defense: (1) build-time guards on `TopologyBuilder` to catch invalid configurations before they reach production, (2) runtime `warn!` logs at routing decision points so operators know when messages are being discarded or retried without delay, (3) doc comment corrections so the documented behavior matches the actual code.\n\n**Tech Stack:** Rust, `tracing` for logging, `lapin` (RabbitMQ), `aws-sdk-sqs` (SQS)\n\n---\n\n## File Structure\n\n| File | Responsibility |\n|---|---|\n| `src/topology.rs` | Build-time validation guards in `TopologyBuilder::build()` |\n| `src/outcome.rs` | Doc comment corrections |\n| `src/backends/rabbitmq/router.rs` | Runtime warnings for RabbitMQ routing |\n| `src/backends/sns/router.rs` | Runtime warnings for SQS routing |\n\nNo new files needed — all changes are edits to existing files.\n\n---\n\n### Task 1: Add `warn!` log when RabbitMQ rejects without a DLQ\n\nThe `route_reject` function in the RabbitMQ router currently nacks without requeue and logs nothing. The doc on `Outcome::Reject` claims a warning is logged — but it isn't. We need the topology available at the call site to know whether a DLQ exists.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `src/backends/rabbitmq/router.rs:95-105` — add `topology` param, log warning when no DLQ\n- Modify: `src/backends/rabbitmq/consumer.rs` — update all `route_reject` call sites to pass topology\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Update `route_reject` signature and add the warning**\n\nChange `route_reject` in `src/backends/rabbitmq/router.rs` from:\n\n```rust\npub(crate) async fn route_reject(delivery: &Delivery) {\n    if let Err(e) = delivery\n        .nack(BasicNackOptions {\n            requeue: false,\n            ..BasicNackOptions::default()\n        })\n        .await\n    {\n        error!(\"failed to nack-reject delivery: {e}\");\n    }\n}\n```\n\nto:\n\n```rust\npub(crate) async fn route_reject(delivery: &Delivery, topology: &QueueTopology) {\n    if topology.dlq().is_none() {\n        warn!(\n            queue = topology.queue(),\n            \"rejecting message on queue with no DLQ configured — message will be discarded\"\n        );\n    }\n    if let Err(e) = delivery\n        .nack(BasicNackOptions {\n            requeue: false,\n            ..BasicNackOptions::default()\n        })\n        .await\n    {\n        error!(\"failed to nack-reject delivery: {e}\");\n    }\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Update all `route_reject` call sites in `src/backends/rabbitmq/consumer.rs`**\n\nSearch the file for every `router::route_reject(&delivery).await` and change to `router::route_reject(&delivery, topology).await`. There are multiple call sites:\n\n1. `route_outcome` function (~line 886): `Outcome::Reject => router::route_reject(delivery, topology).await,`\n2. The `try_deserialize_or_reject` function — find the call and pass topology.\n3. The `max_pending_per_key` rejection path — pass topology.\n4. The poisoned-key rejection paths in the sequenced consumer — pass topology.\n\nFor the `route_outcome` function, topology is already a parameter. For helper functions that call `route_reject` directly, thread `topology` through as a parameter.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Verify it compiles**\n\nRun: `cargo check -q`\nExpected: No errors\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run existing tests**\n\nRun: `cargo test -q`\nExpected: All existing tests pass (the router unit tests don't call `route_reject` directly since it needs a real `Delivery` nack)\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add src/backends/rabbitmq/router.rs src/back